The '''barking imperial pigeon''' ('''''Ducula latrans'''''), also known as '''Peale's imperial pigeon''', is a species of bird in the pigeon [[family (biology)|family]] [[Columbidae]]. It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Fiji]], where it occurs on most of the medium and large islands.<ref name="Mahler et al 2003">{{cite journal |last1=Mahler |first1=Bettina |last2=Araujo |first2=Lidia S. |last3=Tubaro |first3=Pablo L. |title=Dietary and Sexual Correlates of Carotenoid Pigment Expression in Dove Plumage |journal=The Condor |date=2003 |volume=105 |issue=2 |pages=258–267 |jstor=1370545 |doi=10.1093/condor/105.2.258 |doi-access=free }}</ref><ref name="Wragg et al 2006">{{cite journal |last1=Wragg |first1=Graham M. |last2=Worthy |first2=T.H. |title=A new species of extinct imperial pigeon (Ducula: Columbidae) from Henderson Island, Pitcairn Group |journal=Historical Biology |date=January 2006 |volume=18 |issue=2 |pages=131–144 |doi=10.1080/08912960600640853 |bibcode=2006HBio...18..131W |s2cid=83945006 }}</ref>

Its natural [[habitat]]s are mature tropical moist lowland [[forest]]s and tropical moist [[montane forest]]. The species is one of two imperial-pigeons found in Fiji; the other, the [[Pacific imperial pigeon]], is found on smaller islands.{{fact|date=October 2019}}

==Description==
The barking imperial pigeon is frugivorous, feeding on large fruits of the trees ''[[Cananga]]'', ''[[Didymocheton]]'', and ''[[Myristica]]'' (nutmegs). It feeds alone or in pairs, occasionally occurring in small flocks on fruiting trees. The breeding season of this species is from May to January, with a single egg being laid on an insubstantial twig [[bird nest|nest]]. These birds are typically 40-44cm. The upper parts of this bird are grey. The upper wings and upper tail are a darker shade of brown. It has a black bill and the eyes are purple and red. Additionally, the bird got its name because it known to make loud barking "u-oo" in long series. Also, they make a "raa" noise. These calling are often associated with mating. Due to human hunting and interference the habitat for this bird is being put in danger and there has been a decline in the population of these birds!<ref name="Mahler et al 2003" /><ref name="Wragg et al 2006" /><ref name="Cibois et al 2017">{{cite journal |last1=Cibois |first1=Alice |last2=Thibault |first2=Jean-Claude |last3=Bonillo |first3=Céline |last4=Filardi |first4=Christopher E. |last5=Pasquet |first5=Eric |title=Phylogeny and biogeography of the imperial pigeons (Aves: Columbidae) in the Pacific Ocean |journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution |date=May 2017 |volume=110 |pages=19–26 |doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2017.02.016 |pmid=28249741 |bibcode=2017MolPE.110...19C }}</ref>

